VALUES
(42, 3, 14, 50, 4, 11, 11, 'be content with your wages', 'Contentment in Different Contexts', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being content. In Luke, soldiers are instructed to be content with their wages, while Philippians speaks of contentment in any situation.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 14, 54, 6, 8, 10, 'be content with your wages', 'Contentment and Wealth', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being content with what one has. Luke 3:14 advises soldiers to be content with their wages, while 1 Timothy 6:8 encourages contentment with food and raiment, warning against the dangers of desiring wealth.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 14, 3, 19, 11, 11, 'neither accuse any falsely', 'Ethical Conduct in Relationships', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of honesty and integrity in interactions with others. Luke 3:14''s admonition to ''neither accuse any falsely'' parallels Leviticus 19:11''s directive to ''deal falsely'' with one another.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 14, 45, 13, 9, 10, 'Do violence to no man', 'Connection of Ethical Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize ethical behavior towards others, particularly in refraining from harm and falsehood. Luke 3:14''s call to ''Do violence to no man'' resonates with Romans 13:9-10''s directive to ''Love worketh no ill to his neighbour.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 15, 43, 10, 24, 24, 'whether he were the Christ, or not', 'Expectation of the Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s questioning of whether John or Jesus is the Christ. In Luke, the people are in expectation, while in John, they directly ask Jesus if he is the Christ, reflecting their doubt and desire for clarity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 15, 43, 3, 28, 29, 'whether he were the Christ, or not', 'John''s Role as Forerunner', 'This connection highlights John''s acknowledgment of his role as a forerunner to the Christ. Both passages emphasize the expectation of the people regarding the identity of the Messiah and John''s clarification of his own position.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 15, 43, 1, 19, 28, 'whether he were the Christ, or not', 'John''s Identity and Expectation', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s expectation of John as the Christ. In Luke, the people muse about John''s identity, while in John, he explicitly denies being the Christ, clarifying his role as a forerunner.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 16, 40, 3, 11, 11, 'he shall baptize you with the Holy Ghost and with fire', 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the act of baptism and the one who is mightier, highlighting the transition from water baptism to baptism with the Holy Ghost and fire.', 'parallel', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 16, 44, 1, 5, 5, NULL, 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'This connection highlights the theme of baptism, specifically the transition from John''s water baptism to the promised baptism with the Holy Ghost. Both passages emphasize the significance of the Holy Spirit in the context of baptism.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 16, 44, 11, 15, 16, NULL, 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the baptism with the Holy Ghost, linking John''s prophecy to its fulfillment in Acts. John foretells a greater baptism, which is realized when the Holy Ghost falls on the believers.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 16, 43, 1, 33, 33, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the act of baptizing with the Holy Ghost. John the Baptist refers to a mightier one who will baptize with the Holy Ghost and fire, while he himself is instructed to baptize with water and recognizes the one who baptizes with the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 16, 43, 1, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection of John''s Baptism', 'Both passages emphasize John''s role in baptizing with water while pointing to a greater figure who will baptize with the Holy Spirit. This connection highlights the transition from John''s baptism to the more profound baptism that Jesus will provide.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 16, 29, 2, 28, 29, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Spirit and Baptism', 'This connection highlights the theme of the Holy Spirit being poured out. Both passages emphasize the transformative power of the Spirit, with John referencing baptism with the Holy Ghost and Joel speaking of God''s Spirit being poured out on all flesh.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 16, 23, 4, 4, 4, 'baptize you with the Holy Ghost and with fire', 'Connection of Baptism and Purification', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of purification through spiritual means. Luke speaks of baptism with the Holy Ghost and fire, while Isaiah mentions purging by the spirit of judgment and burning.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 17, 24, 15, 7, 7, 'fan is in his hand', 'Imagery of Fanning and Purging', 'Both passages emphasize the act of fanning as a means of separation. In Luke, the fanning leads to the gathering of wheat and burning of chaff, while in Jeremiah, it signifies the bereavement and destruction of people who do not return to their ways.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 17, 40, 13, 30, 30, 'gather the wheat into', 'Harvest and Separation Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of wheat and the burning of chaff or tares at harvest time. This connection highlights the theme of judgment and separation between the righteous and the wicked.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 17, 33, 4, 12, 12, 'gather the wheat into his garner', 'Gathering and Purging Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of wheat and sheaves, highlighting a process of sorting and purging. Luke speaks of gathering wheat into a garner, while Micah refers to gathering sheaves into the floor.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 17, 19, 1, 4, 4, 'the chaff he will burn', 'Chaff Imagery in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of chaff as representing the ungodly or unworthy. Luke 3:17 describes the chaff being burned, while Psalms 1:4 illustrates the chaff being driven away, highlighting a similar fate for the ungodly.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 17, 23, 30, 24, 24, 'purge his floor', 'Winnowing and Purging Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of winnowing and purging in both passages. Luke 3:17 speaks of purging the floor and gathering wheat, while Isaiah 30:24 mentions winnowed provender, suggesting a thematic link in the process of separating valuable grain from chaff.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 17, 40, 3, 12, 12, 'he will throughly purge his floor', 'Connection of Purging and Gathering', 'Both passages emphasize the act of purging and gathering, using similar language to describe the process of separating wheat from chaff. The imagery of the fan and unquenchable fire is consistent in both texts, highlighting the theme of judgment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 17, 19, 21, 9, 10, NULL, 'Fire and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine judgment through fire. Luke 3:17 speaks of burning the chaff, while Psalms 21:9-10 describes a fiery oven in God''s anger, highlighting the destructive nature of divine wrath.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 18, 43, 1, 29, 29, 'his exhortation preached he unto the people', 'John''s Proclamation of Jesus', 'This connection highlights John''s role as a preacher, as indicated in Luke 3:18, and his declaration of Jesus as the Lamb of God in John 1:29. Both passages emphasize the significance of John''s message to the people regarding Jesus'' mission.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 18, 43, 1, 34, 34, 'his exhortation preached he unto the people', 'Connection of Exhortation and Testimony', 'This connection highlights the role of John the Baptist in proclaiming the identity of Jesus. In Luke, John preaches to the people, while in John, he testifies that Jesus is the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 18, 43, 3, 29, 36, 'exhortation preached he unto the people', 'Joy and Exhortation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of joy in both passages. In Luke, John the Baptist''s exhortation brings joy to the people, while in John, the friend of the bridegroom rejoices at the bridegroom''s voice, indicating fulfillment and joy in recognizing Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 18, 44, 2, 40, 40, 'exhortation', 'Exhortation and Testimony Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of exhortation. Luke 3:18 mentions ''many other things in his exhortation,'' while Acts 2:40 states, ''with many other words did he testify and exhort.'' This connection highlights the continuity of preaching and urging the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 18, 43, 1, 15, 15, 'his exhortation preached he unto the people', 'Witness and Exhortation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of witness in both passages. John the Baptist''s exhortation in Luke aligns with his testimony in John, emphasizing his role in preparing the way for Jesus.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 19, 42, 3, 1, 1, NULL, 'Herod''s Role in Luke', 'Both passages emphasize Herod''s position as tetrarch, linking his authority to the events surrounding John the Baptist''s reproach. This connection highlights the political context in which John confronted Herod about his actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 19, 20, 15, 12, 12, 'reproved by him', 'Reproof and Scorn Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of reproof in both passages. Luke 3:19 discusses Herod being reproved, while Proverbs 15:12 notes that a scorner does not love reproof.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 3, 19, 40, 11, 2, 2, 'reproved by him for Herodias', 'Connection Between John and Herod', 'This connection highlights John the Baptist''s imprisonment due to his reproval of Herod. Both passages emphasize John''s role in confronting evil and his subsequent inquiry about Jesus'' works while in prison.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
